Using the disc method of integration, we know that the volume of the
solid can be expressed as follows:

\begin{align*}V = \int_{0}^{m}\pi (\sqrt{x})^{2}\,dx = \int_{0}^{m}\pi x\,dx = \pi \frac{m^{2}}{2}.\end{align*}

We want the value of $m$ such that the volume is equal to $2\pi$, so we
solve the equation:

\begin{align*}\pi\frac{m^{2}}{2} = 2\pi \quad \rightarrow \quad m = \pm 2.\end{align*}

Taking the positive solution gives us our answer\begin{align*}m = 2.\end{align*}
